   7 | The Hill equation with concentration-dependent half-time:
   8 | 
   9 |     y = c3 * x0^c0 / ((c1 * x1^c2)^c0 + x0^c0) + c4
  10 | 
  11 | Physical interpretation:
  12 |   - c0: Hill / nucleation exponent (cooperativity, typically 2-5)
  13 |   - c1: half-time scale factor
  14 |   - c2: concentration exponent for half-time (power-law scaling with x1)
  15 |   - c3: plateau amplitude (~1 for rescaled data)
  16 |   - c4: baseline offset (~0 for rescaled data)
  17 | 
  18 | The term (c1 * x1^c2) is the effective half-time: when x2=0, it collapses
  19 | to a pure constant c1, handling single-concentration datasets; when c2!=0,
  20 | it captures how aggregation rate scales with concentration (e.g. secondary
  21 | nucleation gives c2 ~ -1 to -2, meaning higher concentration → faster).
  22 | 
  23 | Multiple starting points are tried (varying Hill exponent, half-time scale,
  24 | and concentration exponent), with data-driven half-time estimation, and the
  25 | best validation NMSE is returned.
